<PageTitle>Admin Dashboard Step 10: Route Protection & Roles - Example</PageTitle>

<div class="min-h-screen py-8 rounded-4xl bg-gray-50">
    <div class="w-full mx-auto px-4 max-w-5xl">
        <!-- Back link -->
        <a href="/admin-dashboard-guide"
            class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 text-sm sm:text-base text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-700 mb-4">
            <span>‚Üê</span> Back to Admin Dashboard Guide
        </a>

        <!-- Title -->
        <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">
            üîê Step 10: Route Protection &amp; Roles
        </h1>

        <!-- Description -->
        <p class="text-xl text-gray-600 mb-8">
            Lock down your <code>/profile</code>, <code>/analytics</code>, and <code>/admin/dashboard</code> pages so
            only signed-in (and optionally admin) users can access them, with clear messaging when access is denied.
        </p>

        <!-- What You'll Learn (Phase 3 gradient) -->
        <div class="bg-gradient-to-r from-gray-100 to-blue-100 rounded-2xl p-5 sm:p-6 mb-6">
            <h2 class="text-xl sm:text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-4">What You'll Learn</h2>
            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4 text-sm sm:text-base">
                In this step, you'll add authorization checks around your key admin pages so only the right users can
                view or use them.
            </p>
            <ul class="list-disc ml-6 text-sm sm:text-base text-gray-700 space-y-2 mb-4">
                <li>Checking whether a user is signed in before showing protected content.</li>
                <li>Redirecting unauthenticated users to <code>/signin</code> when they try to access protected pages.
                </li>
                <li>Using roles (like <code>"Admin"</code>) to hide or disable sensitive areas.</li>
                <li>Displaying friendly "Access denied" messaging instead of generic errors.</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="mt-2 pt-3 border-t border-blue-200">
                <p class="text-xs sm:text-sm text-gray-700 mb-2">
                    <strong>üí° Key Concepts:</strong> route protection, role-based access control (RBAC), conditional
                    rendering, redirects.
                </p>
                <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-2">
                    <span class="text-xs sm:text-sm text-gray-600">‚Üí Related tips:</span>
                    <a href="/tips#blazor-routing-basics"
                        class="px-3 py-1 bg-blue-100 text-blue-700 rounded-full text-[11px] sm:text-xs font-medium hover:bg-blue-200 transition-colors">Blazor
                        routing basics</a>
                    <a href="/tips#blazor-authorization-checks"
                        class="px-3 py-1 bg-blue-100 text-blue-700 rounded-full text-[11px] sm:text-xs font-medium hover:bg-blue-200 transition-colors">Blazor
                        authorization checks</a>
                    <a href="/tips#role-based-access-control"
                        class="px-3 py-1 bg-blue-100 text-blue-700 rounded-full text-[11px] sm:text-xs font-medium hover:bg-blue-200 transition-colors">Role-based
                        access control</a>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Sample Component: Protected Analytics Page -->
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6 border border-gray-200 mb-6">
            <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">üß© Sample Component: ProtectedAnalyticsPage</h2>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-4">
                This sample shows how you might protect your real <code>/analytics</code> page using a simple
                <code>AuthService</code> that exposes the current user and their roles.
            </p>

            <div class="bg-gray-100 border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto mb-4">
                <div class="text-xs text-gray-500 mb-1">Components/Pages/Analytics.razor (protected)</div>
                <p class="text-xs text-gray-600 mb-2">Wraps the analytics layout in an authorization check and
                    redirects unauthenticated users to <code>/signin</code>.</p>
                <ul class="list-disc ml-4 mb-3 text-[11px] text-gray-600 space-y-1">
                    <li>Uses an injected <code>AuthService</code> to check if the user is signed in.</li>
                    <li>Redirects anonymous users to <code>/signin</code> with a <code>returnUrl</code> query string.
                    </li>
                    <li>Shows a friendly message if the user is signed in but lacks an admin role.</li>
                </ul>
                <pre data-code-title="Components/Pages/Analytics.razor (protected)"
                    class="code-block text-xs sm:text-sm font-mono text-gray-800 w-full max-w-full overflow-x-auto">@@page "/analytics"
@@inject NavigationManager Navigation
@@inject AuthService Auth

&lt;PageTitle&gt;Analytics&lt;/PageTitle&gt;

@@if (!Auth.IsSignedIn)
{
    &lt;!-- Redirect anonymous users to /signin with a returnUrl --&gt;
    @@code {
        protected override void OnInitialized()
        {
            var returnUrl = Navigation.ToBaseRelativePath(Navigation.Uri);
            Navigation.NavigateTo($"/signin?returnUrl={returnUrl}");
        }
    }
}
else if (!Auth.IsInRole("Admin"))
{
    &lt;div class="max-w-xl mx-auto p-6 mt-8 bg-yellow-50 border border-yellow-200 rounded-xl"&gt;
        &lt;h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-yellow-900 mb-2"&gt;Limited access&lt;/h2&gt;
        &lt;p class="text-sm text-yellow-800"&gt;
            You're signed in, but your account doesn't have permission to view detailed analytics.
            Ask an admin to grant you access, or continue using the rest of the dashboard.
        &lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
}
else
{
    &lt;!-- Existing analytics dashboard layout from Step 7/8 goes here --&gt;
    &lt;div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto p-6"&gt;
        &lt;h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6"&gt;Analytics Dashboard&lt;/h1&gt;
        &lt;p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-4"&gt;Summary cards, CSS-only visuals, and recent activity for admins.&lt;/p&gt;
        &lt;!-- ...rest of your analytics content... --&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
}</pre>
            </div>

            <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-2">Step-by-step breakdown</h3>
            <div class="grid gap-4">
                <div class="bg-gray-100 border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4">
                    <div class="text-xs text-gray-500 mb-1">1. Check authentication and redirect if needed</div>
                    <p class="text-xs text-gray-600 mb-2">Use your existing <code>AuthService</code> (from earlier
                        steps) to determine if the user is signed in and send anonymous users to <code>/signin</code>.
                    </p>
                    <ul class="list-disc ml-4 mb-2 text-[11px] text-gray-600 space-y-1">
                        <li>Inject <code>AuthService</code> and <code>NavigationManager</code> at the top of the page.
                        </li>
                        <li>If <code>Auth.IsSignedIn</code> is <code>false</code>, redirect to
                            <code>/signin?returnUrl=/analytics</code>.
                        </li>
                        <li>Keep this logic close to the top so unauthorized users never see protected content.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <pre
                        class="code-block text-xs sm:text-sm font-mono text-gray-800 w-full max-w-full overflow-x-auto">@@inject NavigationManager Navigation
@@inject AuthService Auth

@@if (!Auth.IsSignedIn)
{
    @@code {
        protected override void OnInitialized()
        {
            var returnUrl = Navigation.ToBaseRelativePath(Navigation.Uri);
            Navigation.NavigateTo($"/signin?returnUrl={returnUrl}");
        }
    }
}</pre>
                </div>
                <div class="bg-gray-100 border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4">
                    <div class="text-xs text-gray-500 mb-1">2. Add a simple role check</div>
                    <p class="text-xs text-gray-600 mb-2">Once the user is signed in, use a role check (for example,
                        <code>"Admin"</code>) to decide whether to show analytics or a limited-access message.
                    </p>
                    <ul class="list-disc ml-4 mb-2 text-[11px] text-gray-600 space-y-1">
                        <li>Use a helper like <code>Auth.IsInRole("Admin")</code> to centralize the role logic.</li>
                        <li>Show a clear explanation when users don't have access instead of a blank page.</li>
                        <li>Keep the admin-only layout in the <code>else</code> block so it's only rendered for
                            authorized users.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <pre
                        class="code-block text-xs sm:text-sm font-mono text-gray-800 w-full max-w-full overflow-x-auto">else if (!Auth.IsInRole("Admin"))
{
    &lt;div class="max-w-xl mx-auto p-6 mt-8 bg-yellow-50 border border-yellow-200 rounded-xl"&gt;
        &lt;h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-yellow-900 mb-2"&gt;Limited access&lt;/h2&gt;
        &lt;p class="text-sm text-yellow-800"&gt;You're signed in, but your account doesn't have permission.&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
}
else
{
    &lt;!-- Admin-only analytics content --&gt;
}</pre>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Important Notes & Tips -->
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6 border border-gray-200 mb-6">
            <h2 class="text-xl sm:text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-4">üìù Important Notes & Tips</h2>
            <div class="space-y-3">
                <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4">
                    <h3 class="text-sm font-bold text-blue-900 mb-3">üí° Pro Tips</h3>
                    <div class="space-y-4">
                        <div>
                            <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-2">Don't protect the signin/signup pages
                            </p>
                            <p class="text-xs text-blue-800">Make sure <code>/signin</code> and <code>/signup</code>
                                stay publicly accessible so users can always reach them even if they're not signed in.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                        <div>
                            <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-2">Keep authorization logic in services</p>
                            <p class="text-xs text-blue-800">Expose helpers like <code>IsSignedIn</code> and
                                <code>IsInRole</code> from your auth service instead of sprinkling raw claims checks all
                                over the UI.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                        <div>
                            <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-2">Show clear access-denied messaging</p>
                            <p class="text-xs text-blue-800">A short explanation and a link back to the dashboard is
                                much friendlier than a blank page or generic error when users lack permissions.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="bg-yellow-50 border border-yellow-200 rounded-lg p-4">
                    <h3 class="text-sm font-bold text-yellow-900 mb-2">‚ö†Ô∏è Troubleshooting</h3>
                    <ul class="list-disc ml-6 text-sm text-yellow-900 space-y-1">
                        <li>If users get stuck in a redirect loop, double-check that the signin page itself is not
                            protected by the same checks.</li>
                        <li>If admins are treated as regular users, confirm the role name matches exactly (e.g.,
                            <code>"Admin"</code> vs <code>"admin"</code>).
                        </li>
                        <li>If your auth service isn't available in a component, make sure it's registered in DI and
                            injected with <code>@@inject</code>.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- How to do it (Phase 3 gradient) -->
        <div class="bg-gradient-to-r from-orange-100 to-red-100 rounded-xl p-6 mb-6">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-4">üõ†Ô∏è How to do it</h2>
            <ol class="list-decimal ml-5 space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                <li>
                    <strong>Expose auth helpers:</strong>
                    Update your existing <code>AuthService</code> so it has properties like <code>IsSignedIn</code>,
                    <code>CurrentUser</code>, and an <code>IsInRole(string role)</code> helper.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Protect /profile and /analytics:</strong>
                    At the top of each page, inject <code>AuthService</code> and perform an <code>IsSignedIn</code>
                    check. Redirect anonymous users to <code>/signin</code> with a <code>returnUrl</code>.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Add an admin-only layer to /admin/dashboard:</strong>
                    Use <code>IsInRole("Admin")</code> to decide whether to show the full dashboard shell or a
                    limited-access message.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Test all paths:</strong>
                    Try visiting protected routes while signed out, signed in as a regular user, and signed in as an
                    admin to confirm behavior matches expectations.
                </li>
            </ol>
        </div>

        <!-- Live Demo -->
        <div class="bg-black/3 rounded-2xl p-6 mb-6">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-4">üé¨ Live Demo</h2>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-4">
                This mock shows what users see when they hit a protected page depending on their sign-in state and
                role.
            </p>

            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
                <!-- Anonymous user card -->
                <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl border border-gray-200 p-4 flex flex-col">
                    <div class="flex items-center justify-between mb-3">
                        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-900">Anonymous user ‚Üí /analytics</h3>
                        <span
                            class="px-2 py-1 text-[11px] rounded-full bg-gray-100 text-gray-700">Unauthenticated</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="flex-1 flex items-center justify-center">
                        <p class="text-xs text-gray-600 text-center">
                            Immediately redirected to <span
                                class="font-mono text-gray-800">/signin?returnUrl=/analytics</span>.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Signed-in non-admin card -->
                <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl border border-gray-200 p-4 flex flex-col">
                    <div class="flex items-center justify-between mb-3">
                        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-900">User (no admin role)</h3>
                        <span class="px-2 py-1 text-[11px] rounded-full bg-yellow-100 text-yellow-800">Limited</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="bg-yellow-50 border border-yellow-200 rounded-xl p-3 flex-1 flex items-center">
                        <p class="text-xs text-yellow-900">
                            Sees "Limited access" card instead of the analytics dashboard, with guidance to contact an
                            admin.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Admin card -->
                <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl border border-gray-200 p-4 flex flex-col">
                    <div class="flex items-center justify-between mb-3">
                        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-900">Admin user</h3>
                        <span class="px-2 py-1 text-[11px] rounded-full bg-emerald-100 text-emerald-800">Full
                            access</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="flex-1">
                        <div class="bg-gray-50 border border-gray-200 rounded-xl p-3 mb-3">
                            <p class="text-xs text-gray-700 mb-1">‚úÖ Sees full analytics dashboard</p>
                            <p class="text-[11px] text-gray-500">Summary cards, CSS-only visuals, and recent activity
                                are all visible.</p>
                        </div>
                        <ul class="list-disc ml-4 text-[11px] text-gray-600 space-y-1">
                            <li>Can view <code>/profile</code>, <code>/analytics</code>, and
                                <code>/admin/dashboard</code>.</li>
                            <li>May see extra admin-only cards or navigation links.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <p class="text-xs text-gray-600 mt-4 text-center">
                üí° You can reuse this pattern for any future admin-only pages: check auth, check roles, then render the
                appropriate view.
            </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Mark Complete Section -->
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6 border-2 border-green-200 mb-6">
            <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row sm:items-center sm:justify-between gap-4">
                <div>
                    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-1">Finished Step 10?</h3>
